    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.treesitter.query.get('c', 'highlights')` raises:\n\n```\nQuery error at 209:29. Invalid syntax:\n    \"__FILE__\" \"__LINE__\" \"\"%{b} %{d} %{Y}\"\" \"\"%{H}:%{M}\"\"\n                            ^\n```\n\nThe error originates at `runtime/lua/vim/treesitter/query.lua:373` (`vim._ts_parse_query`). The whole c highlights query becomes unparseable, breaking treesitter highlighting for C files. Downstream traceback observed via snacks.nvim picker:\n\n```\n[C]: in function '_ts_parse_query'\nruntime/lua/vim/treesitter/query.lua:373: in function 'fn'\nruntime/lua/vim/func/_memoize.lua:78: in function 'fn'\nruntime/lua/vim/func/_memoize.lua:78: in function 'get'\n~/.local/share/nvim/lazy/snacks.nvim/lua/snacks/picker/util/highlight.lua:54: in function 'fn'\nruntime/lua/vim/treesitter/languagetree.lua:650: in function 'for_each_tree'\n~/.local/share/nvim/lazy/snacks.nvim/lua/snacks/picker/util/highlight.lua:50: in function 'get_highlights'\n~/.local/share/nvim/lazy/snacks.nvim/lua/snacks/picker/util/highlight.lua:236: in function 'format'\n```\n\n### Suggested fix\n\nDelete the two malformed tokens on line 209:\n\n```diff\n-    \"__FILE__\" \"__LINE__\" \"\"%{b} %{d} %{Y}\"\" \"\"%{H}:%{M}\"\"\n+    \"__FILE__\" \"__LINE__\"\n```\n\nEquivalent one-liner used locally as a workaround:\n\n```bash\nsudo sed -i 's| \"\"%{b} %{d} %{Y}\"\" \"\"%{H}:%{M}\"\"||' /usr/share/nvim/runtime/queries/c/highlights.scm\n```\n\nWrapping `vim.treesitter.query.parse` in a `pcall` that returns `nil` on failure also prevents downstream crashes, but loses treesitter highlighting for c until the file itself is patched.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nBug is in a bundled runtime query, so no plugins or user config are needed.\n\n```\nnvim --clean\n:lua vim.print({ pcall(vim.treesitter.query.get, 'c', 'highlights') })\n```\n\nThe bundled c parser ships with Neovim 0.11, so the parse is triggered immediately. Equivalently, opening any `.c` file with treesitter highlighting enabled triggers the same path.\n\nThe malformed tokens are at `runtime/queries/c/highlights.scm:209`:\n\n```\n\"__FILE__\" \"__LINE__\" \"\"%{b} %{d} %{Y}\"\" \"\"%{H}:%{M}\"\"\n                        ^\n```\n\n`\"\"%{b} %{d} %{Y}\"\"` and `\"\"%{H}:%{M}\"\"` are not valid string literals — the doubled empty-quote-then-string sequence is rejected by the tree-sitter query parser, which makes the entire `c` highlights query unusable. They also don't belong in this `#any-of?` predicate, which matches predefined C identifiers (`__FILE__`, `__LINE__`, `__STDC__`, …); `%{b} %{d} %{Y}` and `%{H}:%{M}` are strftime / log-format strings, not identifiers. They appear to have been pasted in by accident.\n\nLines 205–215 for context:\n\n```scheme\n((identifier) @constant.builtin\n  ; format-ignore\n  (#any-of? @constant.builtin\n    \"stderr\" \"stdin\" \"stdout\"\n    \"__FILE__\" \"__LINE__\" \"\"%{b} %{d} %{Y}\"\" \"\"%{H}:%{M}\"\"\n    \"__STDC__\" \"__STDC_VERSION__\" \"__STDC_HOSTED__\"\n    \"__cplusplus\" \"__OBJC__\" \"__ASSEMBLER__\"\n    \"__BASE_FILE__\" \"__FILE_NAME__\" \"__INCLUDE_LEVEL__\"\n    \"__TIMESTAMP__\" \"__clang__\" \"__clang_major__\"\n    \"__clang_minor__\" \"__clang_patchlevel__\"\n    \"__clang_version__\" \"__clang_literal_encoding__\"\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`vim.treesitter.query.get('c', 'highlights')` returns a parsed query, and treesitter-based highlighting works on C files. Downstream consumers that call `vim.treesitter.query.parse('c', ...)` (e.g. picker UIs that highlight grep results) do not crash.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.5 Build type: RelWithDebInfo LuaJIT 2.1.1756211046\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A — the bug is in a Neovim runtime asset (runtime/queries/c/highlights.scm) which Vim does not use.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nopenSUSE Tumbleweed under WSL2 (kernel 6.6.87.2-microsoft-standard-WSL2 x86_64)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal \n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nsystem package manager (zypper, openSUSE Tumbleweed)",
